T1  - The Allocation of Credit and Financial Collapse*
PY  - 1986
Y1  - 1986/08/01
DO  - 10.2307/1885692
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 101
IS  - 3
SP  - 455
EP  - 470
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - This paper examines the allocation of credit in a market in which borrowers have greater information concerning their own riskiness than do lenders. It illustrates that (1) the allocation of credit is inefficient and at times can be improved by government intervention, and (2) small changes in the exogenous risk-free interest rate can cause large (discontinuous) changes in the allocation of credit and the efficiency of the market equilibrium. These conclusions suggests a role for government as the lender of last resort.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/1885692
ER  - 



